solution: ```class Solution {
    public int numRollsToTarget(int n, int k, int target) {
        final int MOD = 1_000_000_007;
        if (target < n || target > n * k) return 0;
        int[] dp = new int[target + 1];
        dp[0] = 1;
        for (int dice = 1; dice <= n; dice++) {
            int[] next = new int[target + 1];
            for (int sum = dice; sum <= Math.min(target, dice * k); sum++) {
                long ways = 0;
                for (int face = 1; face <= k && face <= sum; face++) {
                    ways += dp[sum - face];
                    if (ways >= MOD) ways -= MOD;
                }
                next[sum] = (int) ways;
            }
            dp = next;
        }
        return dp[target];
    }
}
```
efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: O(n * target * k)
space complexity: O(target)
energy implications: LOW
explanation: Uses dynamic programming with a rolling 1-D array to count ways to reach each sum with exactly i dice. The inner loop iterates over possible face values, summing valid previous states. The rolling array reduces memory usage from O(n * target) to O(target).

